{"title_page": "Prostitution in Egypt", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n'''Prostitution in Egypt''' is illegal.<ref>{{cite web |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714201301/http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaEgypt.pdf |archive-date=14 July 2007 |title=Legislation of Interpol member states on sexual offences against children - Egypt |url=http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaEgypt.pdf|website=Interpol|accessdate=2 April 2018|date= 2006}}</ref> The [[Egyptian National Police]] officially combats prostitution but, like almost all other countries, prostitution exists in Egypt. [[UNAIDS]] estimate there to be 23,000 prostitutes in the country,<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref> including [[Egyptians]], [[Eastern Europeans]], and of many other nationalities.<ref name=alahram>{{cite newspaper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317024659/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2001/537/chrncls.htm|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2001/537/chrncls.htm|title=A Diwan of contemporary life|author=Dr Yunan Labib Rizk|newspaper=Al-Ahram Weekly|date=7\u201313 June 2001|archive-date=17 March 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2070639.stm \"Egypt deports 'east European prostitutes'\"] BBC News, 27 June 2002</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422014338/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2007/833/eg5.htm|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2007/833/eg5.htm|title=Devil in the detail|author=Shaden Shehab|newspaper=Al-Ahram Weekly|date=22\u201328 February 2007|archive-date=22 April 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/28109 \"The Virgin Prostitute!\"] by Marwa Rakha, ''American Chronicle'', 29 May 2007</ref>\n\n== History==\n===Ancient Egypt===\nProstitutes in Ancient Egypt were respected and even considered sacred as the first institutions where prostitution flourished were the temples of the Gods.<ref name=\"unesco\">{{cite web\n | url = http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0006/000661/066103eb.pdf\n | title = Prostitution in Egypt\n | last = El Saadawi\n | first = Narwal  \n | date = 1985\n | website =\n | publisher = UNESCO\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref> The god [[Amun]] indulged in sexual activity with many women under a religious guise. Families often gave their most beautiful daughters to the priests of his temple. As soon as they grew too old for the tastes of the priests they were allowed to leave. Many practised prostitution until they were married.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nSome of the prostitutes wore blue [[fa\u00efence]]-beaded fishnet dresses, had red-painted lips and tattoos on their breasts or thighs.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.thekeep.org/~kunoichi/kunoichi/themestream/sexuality.html\n | title = Ancient Egyptian Sexuality: Life in Ancient Egypt\n | last = Seawright\n | first = Caroline \n | date = 9 April 2001\n | website =\n | publisher = The Keep\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===Roman occupation===\n{{see also|Prostitution in ancient Rome}}\nAs in the rest of the Roman Empire, prostitution was regulated. Prostitutes had to be registered<ref>Edwards, \"Unspeakable Professions,\" p. 81.</ref> and taxes were collected from them.<ref>{{cite book |last= McGinn |first=Thomas A. J. |authorlink= |title=Prostitution, Sexuality, and the Law in Ancient Rome |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BmH31IK-OgEC |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2003|isbn=9780195161328}}</ref>\n\n===Middle Ages===\nProstitution was generally tolerated and taxed during this period,<ref name=\"Gadelrab\">{{cite book |last=Gadelrab |first=Sherry Sayed |authorlink= |year=2016 |title=Medicine and Morality in Egypt: Gender and Sexuality in the Nineteenth and Early Twentieth Centuries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xT5MDAAAQBAJ |publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9780857737724}}</ref> the rulers taking the view that prohibition would not stop prostitution and that tax revenue would be lost.<ref name=\"Gadelrab\" />\n\nThere were periods when prostitution was prohibited following pressure on the rulers from Muslim clerics.<ref name=\"Gadelrab\" />\n\n===Ottoman rule===\nUnder Ottoman rule, the regulation and taxation of prostitutes continued.<ref name=\"semerdjian\">{{cite book |last=Semerdjian |first=Elyse |authorlink= |title=\"Off the Straight Path\": Illicit Sex, Law, and Community in Ottoman Aleppo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZEAEnGz7CLAC |publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2008|isbn=9780815631736}}</ref> During the 17th century two guilds for prostitutes were set up.<ref name=\"semerdjian\" />\n\n===French occupation===\nProstitution flourished following the [[French invasion of Egypt]] in 1798. The French organised additional prostitutes brought over from Europe.<ref name=\"unesco\" /> [[Sexually transmitted infection|STI]]s spread rapidly through the brothels and this prompted the French authorities to introduce a law forbidding French troops from entering a brothel or having prostitutes in their rooms. Offenders received a death penalty.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\n===Rule of Muhammad Ali===\nIn 1834 [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]] outlawed prostitution<ref>{{cite book |last=Ditmore |first=Melissa Hope |date= |title=Encyclopedia of Prostitution and Sex Work: A-N. Vol. 1 |url= |location= |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> and female public dancing in Cairo. The prostitutes and dancers were sent to [[Upper Egypt]], especially [[Qena|Kena]], [[Esna]] and [[Aswan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Dancer Of Esna |url=http://williamhpeck.org/the_dancer_of_esna |website=williamhpeck.org |accessdate=12 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In 1837 he extended this to all of Egypt.<ref name=\"semerdjian\" />\n\nArticle 240 of the Mixed Penal Code of 1867 states: ''A pimp who incites young men or women below the age of 21 to evil practices leading to rape is to be punished by a period of imprisonment not less than one month and not more than one year''.<ref name=\"unesco\" /> Article 241 increases the penalty if the offence is committed by the father, mother or guardian of a minor.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nFollowing the abolition of slavery in 1877, many recently freed female slaves turned to prostitution to survive.<ref name=\"Gadelrab\" />\n\n===British occupation===\n[[File:Prostitute license 1885.jpg|220px|thumb|1885 prostitute license issued in the Cairo municipality]]\nAfter the British occupation of 1882, the authorities were concerned about disease spreading amongst the troops. They made legal provisions to control prostitution and introduced a system of healthcare.<ref name=\"unesco\" /><ref name=\"Gadelrab\" /> In July 1885 Egypt's Ministry of the Interior introduced regulations for the health inspection of prostitutes.<ref name=\"unesco\" /> Further regulations were introduced in 1896 to control brothels.<ref name=\"unesco\" /><ref>{{cite book |last=Bearman |first=Peri |last2=Weiss |first2=Bernard G. |author-link2= |last3=Heinrichs |first3=Wolfhart |author-link3= |year=2008 |title= The Law Applied: Contextualizing the Islamic Shari'a |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OPEBAwAAQBAJ |location= |publisher=I. B. Tauris & Company |page= |isbn=9780857714275 |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nAustralian soldiers stationed in Egypt in [[World War I]] including the famous half Chinese Australian sniper [[Billy Sing#Western Front|Billy Sing]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hamilton|first=John |year=2015|title= Gallipoli Sniper: The Remarkable Life of Billy Sing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekeuCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher=Frontline Books|edition=illustrated |page=2 |isbn=978-1848329041|author-link= }}</ref> were major customers of Egyptian prostitutes in the local red light districts and brothels. High prices by the prostitutes led to the Wasser red light area becoming the scene of a major riot by New Zealand and Australian soldiers on Good Friday in 1915.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hamilton|first=John |year=2015|title= Gallipoli Sniper: The Remarkable Life of Billy Sing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekeuCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher=Frontline Books|edition=illustrated |page=89 |isbn=978-1848329041|author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Robinson |first=Russell |editor-last=Lyons |editor-first= Jo |year= 2014 |title= Khaki Crims and Desperadoes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bD2SAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT50#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher= Macmillan Publishers Aus. |edition=illustrated |page= |isbn= 978-1743518175 |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last= |first=|editor1-last= Damousi |editor1-first= Joy |editor2-last= Lake |editor2-first= Marilyn |year= 1995 |title= Gender and War: Australians at War in the Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fgk4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher=CUP Archive|edition=illustrated|issue=Issue 16 of Studies in Australian History|page= 52|isbn=978-0521457101 |author-link= }}</ref> The Australian military arranged for medical treatment for venereal diseases among its soldiers in Port Said and Cairo.<ref>{{cite book |last= Featherstone |first=Lisa |year= 2011 |title= Let's Talk About Sex: Histories of Sexuality in Australia from Federation to the Pill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfsqBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA110#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher= Cambridge Scholars Publishing |page= 110|isbn= 978-1443828130 |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Australian Medical Association, British Medical Association |year= 1915 |title= Medical Journal of Australia, Band 2|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6LU1AQAAMAAJ&q=erosions+commonest+appearance+australian+cairo|location= |publisher=Australasian Medical Publishing Company|page= 485|isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |author= |year= 1962 |title=Australia in the War of 1939-1945 : Ser. 5. Medical, Band 1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZFQhAQAAIAAJ&q=cases+seen+respiratory+serum+australian+cairo&dq=cases+seen+respiratory+serum+australian+cairo|location= |publisher=Australian War Memorial|page= 235|isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nIn 1932 a Cabinet decree abolished licences for prostitution and established the \"Public Morals Police\".<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nA new penal code was introduced in 1937 and included a section to punish men who lived off the earnings of prostitutes.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nIn 1949 Military Order no. 76 was issued abolishing brothels.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nLaw No. 68, introduced in 1951, penalizing:<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n* Acts of prostitution if carried out habitually\n* Acts of prostitution whether carried out by males or females. (The term ''prostitution'' was used in regard to females; for males the term used was ''licentiousness''.)\n* Acts inciting others to engage in prostitution\n* International trading of prostitutes ([[white slave trade]]) \n* The provision of housing or other premises where prostitutes can carry on their trade\n* The advertisement of prostitution whether in an open or disguised way.\n\n== The prostitution system ==\nThe prostitution system in Egypt often depends on [[pimp]]ing, although women also work alone. Pimps in Egypt organize the work of a group of prostitutes and receive a percentage of their profits. This is called the network in Egypt. This system is mainly used in [[Cairo]] and [[Alexandria]] and other big cities.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==Nikah mut\u2018ah==\n[[Nikah mut\u2018ah]] is a temporary marriage allowed under Shia Islam Law. The 'marriage' may last for a term of one hour to one year. It is sometimes used to circumvent the prostitution laws.<ref name=\"zocalo\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.zocalopublicsquare.org/2010/10/24/what-we-dont-know-about-sex-in-the-middle-east/ideas/up-for-discussion/\n | title = What We Don't Know about Sex in the Middle East\n | last =\n | first =\n | date =25 October 2010\n | website =\n | publisher = Zocalo\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===Summer marriages===\nWealthy men from the Gulf states often holiday in Egypt in the summer months. Whilst there they may take a young, temporary bride (often under-age) in a so-called ''summer marriage''. The marriages are arranged through a marriage broker and the girl's parents receive gifts and money as a 'dowry'. The marriage ends when the men return to their own country.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/scandal-of-summer-brides-7944467.html\n | title = Scandal of 'summer brides'\n | last = Milena\n | first = Veselinovic \n | date = 14 July 2012\n | website =\n | publisher = The Independent\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n== Prostitution in the economy ==\nAs prostitution is illegal in Egypt, no taxes are paid. The law exposes people who practice [[adultery]] to a jail sentence up to six months. For prostitution, the sentence is up to 3 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Countries and Their Prostitution Policies|url=http://prostitution.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=000772#egypt|website=ProCon.org|date=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Egypt}}\nEgypt is a source, transit, and destination country for women and children subjected to sex trafficking. Egyptian children are vulnerable to sex trafficking. Individuals from the Persian Gulf, including Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, and Kuwait purchase Egyptian women and girls for \"temporary\" or \"summer\" marriages for the purpose of commercial sex, including cases of sex trafficking; these arrangements are often facilitated by the victims' parents and marriage brokers, who profit from the transaction. Child sex tourism occurs primarily in Cairo, Alexandria, and Luxor.<ref name=\"state18\">{{cite web |title=Egypt 2018 Trafficking in Persons Report |url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282648.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728191052/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282648.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 July 2018 |website=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=28 July 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nWomen and girls, including refugees and migrants, from Asia, Sub-Saharan Africa, and the Middle East endure sex trafficking in Egypt. Syrian refugees who have settled in Egypt remain increasingly vulnerable to exploitation, including sex trafficking, and transactional marriages of girls\u2014which can lead to sexual exploitation, including sex trafficking,<ref name=\"state18\" />\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Egypt as a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]]' country.<ref name=\"state18\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.hartford-hwp.com/archives/32/021.html \"Sex Tourism in Cairo\"] by Karim el-Gawhary, ''Middle East Report'', Vol. 25, no. 5, September\u2013October 1995; hosted by Hartford Web Publishing\n*[http://www.alternet.org/sex/89597/ \"In Egypt, 'Prostitute' Is a Slippery Term\"] by L.L. Wynn, ''American Sexuality'' magazine, 26 June 2008\n\n==External links==\n* [http://prostitution.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=000772 Prostitution status by country]\n\n{{Africa in topic|Prostitution in}}\n{{Asia in topic|Prostitution in}}\n{{Egypt topics}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution in Egypt| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n'''Prostitution in Egypt''' is illegal.<ref>{{cite web |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714201301/http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaEgypt.pdf |archive-date=14 July 2007 |title=Legislation of Interpol member states on sexual offences against children - Egypt |url=http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaEgypt.pdf|website=Interpol|accessdate=2 April 2018|date= 2006}}</ref> The [[Egyptian National Police]] officially combats prostitution but, like almost all other countries, prostitution exists in Egypt. [[UNAIDS]] estimate there to be 23,000 prostitutes in the country,<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref> including [[Egyptians]], [[Eastern Europe]]ans, and of many other nationalities.<ref name=alahram>{{cite newspaper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317024659/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2001/537/chrncls.htm|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2001/537/chrncls.htm|title=A Diwan of contemporary life|author=Dr Yunan Labib Rizk|newspaper=Al-Ahram Weekly|date=7\u201313 June 2001|archive-date=17 March 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2070639.stm \"Egypt deports 'east European prostitutes'\"] BBC News, 27 June 2002</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422014338/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2007/833/eg5.htm|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2007/833/eg5.htm|title=Devil in the detail|author=Shaden Shehab|newspaper=Al-Ahram Weekly|date=22\u201328 February 2007|archive-date=22 April 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/28109 \"The Virgin Prostitute!\"] by Marwa Rakha, ''American Chronicle'', 29 May 2007</ref>\n\n== History==\n===Ancient Egypt===\nProstitutes in Ancient Egypt were respected and even considered sacred as the first institutions where prostitution flourished were the temples of the Gods.<ref name=\"unesco\">{{cite web\n | url = http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0006/000661/066103eb.pdf\n | title = Prostitution in Egypt\n | last = El Saadawi\n | first = Narwal  \n | date = 1985\n | website =\n | publisher = UNESCO\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref> The god [[Amun]] indulged in sexual activity with many women under a religious guise. Families often gave their most beautiful daughters to the priests of his temple. As soon as they grew too old for the tastes of the priests they were allowed to leave. Many practised prostitution until they were married.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nSome of the prostitutes wore blue [[fa\u00efence]]-beaded fishnet dresses, had red-painted lips and tattoos on their breasts or thighs.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.thekeep.org/~kunoichi/kunoichi/themestream/sexuality.html\n | title = Ancient Egyptian Sexuality: Life in Ancient Egypt\n | last = Seawright\n | first = Caroline \n | date = 9 April 2001\n | website =\n | publisher = The Keep\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===Roman occupation===\n{{see also|Prostitution in ancient Rome}}\nAs in the rest of the Roman Empire, prostitution was regulated. Prostitutes had to be registered<ref>Edwards, \"Unspeakable Professions,\" p. 81.</ref> and taxes were collected from them.<ref>{{cite book |last= McGinn |first=Thomas A. J. |authorlink= |title=Prostitution, Sexuality, and the Law in Ancient Rome |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BmH31IK-OgEC |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2003|isbn=9780195161328}}</ref>\n\n===Middle Ages===\nProstitution was generally tolerated and taxed during this period,<ref name=\"Gadelrab\">{{cite book |last=Gadelrab |first=Sherry Sayed |authorlink= |year=2016 |title=Medicine and Morality in Egypt: Gender and Sexuality in the Nineteenth and Early Twentieth Centuries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xT5MDAAAQBAJ |publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9780857737724}}</ref> the rulers taking the view that prohibition would not stop prostitution and that tax revenue would be lost.<ref name=\"Gadelrab\" />\n\nThere were periods when prostitution was prohibited following pressure on the rulers from Muslim clerics.<ref name=\"Gadelrab\" />\n\n===Ottoman rule===\nUnder Ottoman rule, the regulation and taxation of prostitutes continued.<ref name=\"semerdjian\">{{cite book |last=Semerdjian |first=Elyse |authorlink= |title=\"Off the Straight Path\": Illicit Sex, Law, and Community in Ottoman Aleppo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZEAEnGz7CLAC |publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2008|isbn=9780815631736}}</ref> During the 17th century two guilds for prostitutes were set up.<ref name=\"semerdjian\" />\n\n===French occupation===\nProstitution flourished following the [[French invasion of Egypt]] in 1798. The French organised additional prostitutes brought over from Europe.<ref name=\"unesco\" /> [[Sexually transmitted infection|STI]]s spread rapidly through the brothels and this prompted the French authorities to introduce a law forbidding French troops from entering a brothel or having prostitutes in their rooms. Offenders received a death penalty.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\n===Rule of Muhammad Ali===\nIn 1834 [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]] outlawed prostitution<ref>{{cite book |last=Ditmore |first=Melissa Hope |date= |title=Encyclopedia of Prostitution and Sex Work: A-N. Vol. 1 |url= |location= |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> and female public dancing in Cairo. The prostitutes and dancers were sent to [[Upper Egypt]], especially [[Qena|Kena]], [[Esna]] and [[Aswan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Dancer Of Esna |url=http://williamhpeck.org/the_dancer_of_esna |website=williamhpeck.org |accessdate=12 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In 1837 he extended this to all of Egypt.<ref name=\"semerdjian\" />\n\nArticle 240 of the Mixed Penal Code of 1867 states: ''A pimp who incites young men or women below the age of 21 to evil practices leading to rape is to be punished by a period of imprisonment not less than one month and not more than one year''.<ref name=\"unesco\" /> Article 241 increases the penalty if the offence is committed by the father, mother or guardian of a minor.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nFollowing the abolition of slavery in 1877, many recently freed female slaves turned to prostitution to survive.<ref name=\"Gadelrab\" />\n\n===British occupation===\n[[File:Prostitute license 1885.jpg|220px|thumb|1885 prostitute license issued in the Cairo municipality]]\nAfter the British occupation of 1882, the authorities were concerned about disease spreading amongst the troops. They made legal provisions to control prostitution and introduced a system of healthcare.<ref name=\"unesco\" /><ref name=\"Gadelrab\" /> In July 1885 Egypt's Ministry of the Interior introduced regulations for the health inspection of prostitutes.<ref name=\"unesco\" /> Further regulations were introduced in 1896 to control brothels.<ref name=\"unesco\" /><ref>{{cite book |last=Bearman |first=Peri |last2=Weiss |first2=Bernard G. |author-link2= |last3=Heinrichs |first3=Wolfhart |author-link3= |year=2008 |title= The Law Applied: Contextualizing the Islamic Shari'a |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OPEBAwAAQBAJ |location= |publisher=I. B. Tauris & Company |page= |isbn=9780857714275 |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nAustralian soldiers stationed in Egypt in [[World War I]] including the famous half Chinese Australian sniper [[Billy Sing#Western Front|Billy Sing]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hamilton|first=John |year=2015|title= Gallipoli Sniper: The Remarkable Life of Billy Sing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekeuCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher=Frontline Books|edition=illustrated |page=2 |isbn=978-1848329041|author-link= }}</ref> were major customers of Egyptian prostitutes in the local red light districts and brothels. High prices by the prostitutes led to the Wasser red light area becoming the scene of a major riot by New Zealand and Australian soldiers on Good Friday in 1915.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hamilton|first=John |year=2015|title= Gallipoli Sniper: The Remarkable Life of Billy Sing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekeuCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher=Frontline Books|edition=illustrated |page=89 |isbn=978-1848329041|author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Robinson |first=Russell |editor-last=Lyons |editor-first= Jo |year= 2014 |title= Khaki Crims and Desperadoes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bD2SAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT50#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher= Macmillan Publishers Aus. |edition=illustrated |page= |isbn= 978-1743518175 |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last= |first=|editor1-last= Damousi |editor1-first= Joy |editor2-last= Lake |editor2-first= Marilyn |year= 1995 |title= Gender and War: Australians at War in the Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fgk4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher=CUP Archive|edition=illustrated|issue=Issue 16 of Studies in Australian History|page= 52|isbn=978-0521457101 |author-link= }}</ref> The Australian military arranged for medical treatment for venereal diseases among its soldiers in Port Said and Cairo.<ref>{{cite book |last= Featherstone |first=Lisa |year= 2011 |title= Let's Talk About Sex: Histories of Sexuality in Australia from Federation to the Pill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfsqBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA110#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= |publisher= Cambridge Scholars Publishing |page= 110|isbn= 978-1443828130 |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Australian Medical Association, British Medical Association |year= 1915 |title= Medical Journal of Australia, Band 2|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6LU1AQAAMAAJ&q=erosions+commonest+appearance+australian+cairo|location= |publisher=Australasian Medical Publishing Company|page= 485|isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |author= |year= 1962 |title=Australia in the War of 1939-1945 : Ser. 5. Medical, Band 1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZFQhAQAAIAAJ&q=cases+seen+respiratory+serum+australian+cairo&dq=cases+seen+respiratory+serum+australian+cairo|location= |publisher=Australian War Memorial|page= 235|isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nIn 1932 a Cabinet decree abolished licences for prostitution and established the \"Public Morals Police\".<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nA new penal code was introduced in 1937 and included a section to punish men who lived off the earnings of prostitutes.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nIn 1949 Military Order no. 76 was issued abolishing brothels.<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n\nLaw No. 68, introduced in 1951, penalizing:<ref name=\"unesco\" />\n* Acts of prostitution if carried out habitually\n* Acts of prostitution whether carried out by males or females. (The term ''prostitution'' was used in regard to females; for males the term used was ''licentiousness''.)\n* Acts inciting others to engage in prostitution\n* International trading of prostitutes ([[white slave trade]]) \n* The provision of housing or other premises where prostitutes can carry on their trade\n* The advertisement of prostitution whether in an open or disguised way.\n\n== The prostitution system ==\nThe prostitution system in Egypt often depends on [[pimp]]ing, although women also work alone. Pimps in Egypt organize the work of a group of prostitutes and receive a percentage of their profits. This is called the network in Egypt. This system is mainly used in [[Cairo]] and [[Alexandria]] and other big cities.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==Nikah mut\u2018ah==\n[[Nikah mut\u2018ah]] is a temporary marriage allowed under Shia Islam Law. The 'marriage' may last for a term of one hour to one year. It is sometimes used to circumvent the prostitution laws.<ref name=\"zocalo\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.zocalopublicsquare.org/2010/10/24/what-we-dont-know-about-sex-in-the-middle-east/ideas/up-for-discussion/\n | title = What We Don't Know about Sex in the Middle East\n | last =\n | first =\n | date =25 October 2010\n | website =\n | publisher = Zocalo\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===Summer marriages===\nWealthy men from the Gulf states often holiday in Egypt in the summer months. Whilst there they may take a young, temporary bride (often under-age) in a so-called ''summer marriage''. The marriages are arranged through a marriage broker and the girl's parents receive gifts and money as a 'dowry'. The marriage ends when the men return to their own country.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/scandal-of-summer-brides-7944467.html\n | title = Scandal of 'summer brides'\n | last = Milena\n | first = Veselinovic \n | date = 14 July 2012\n | website =\n | publisher = The Independent\n | access-date = 22 April 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n== Prostitution in the economy ==\nAs prostitution is illegal in Egypt, no taxes are paid. The law exposes people who practice [[adultery]] to a jail sentence up to six months. For prostitution, the sentence is up to 3 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Countries and Their Prostitution Policies|url=http://prostitution.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=000772#egypt|website=ProCon.org|date=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Egypt}}\nEgypt is a source, transit, and destination country for women and children subjected to sex trafficking. Egyptian children are vulnerable to sex trafficking. Individuals from the Persian Gulf, including Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, and Kuwait purchase Egyptian women and girls for \"temporary\" or \"summer\" marriages for the purpose of commercial sex, including cases of sex trafficking; these arrangements are often facilitated by the victims' parents and marriage brokers, who profit from the transaction. Child sex tourism occurs primarily in Cairo, Alexandria, and Luxor.<ref name=\"state18\">{{cite web |title=Egypt 2018 Trafficking in Persons Report |url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282648.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728191052/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282648.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 July 2018 |website=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=28 July 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nWomen and girls, including refugees and migrants, from Asia, Sub-Saharan Africa, and the Middle East endure sex trafficking in Egypt. Syrian refugees who have settled in Egypt remain increasingly vulnerable to exploitation, including sex trafficking, and transactional marriages of girls\u2014which can lead to sexual exploitation, including sex trafficking,<ref name=\"state18\" />\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Egypt as a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]]' country.<ref name=\"state18\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.hartford-hwp.com/archives/32/021.html \"Sex Tourism in Cairo\"] by Karim el-Gawhary, ''Middle East Report'', Vol. 25, no. 5, September\u2013October 1995; hosted by Hartford Web Publishing\n*[http://www.alternet.org/sex/89597/ \"In Egypt, 'Prostitute' Is a Slippery Term\"] by L.L. Wynn, ''American Sexuality'' magazine, 26 June 2008\n\n==External links==\n* [http://prostitution.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=000772 Prostitution status by country]\n\n{{Africa in topic|Prostitution in}}\n{{Asia in topic|Prostitution in}}\n{{Egypt topics}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution in Egypt| ]]\n", "name_user": "Peipsi-Pihkva", "label": "safe", "comment": "Eastern Europeans", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prostitution_in_Egypt"}
